}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"WordPress";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:35:"https://community.1and1.com/?p=9694";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:621:"<p>Only up-to-date software can protect against security holes and attacks. This is true for smartphones, Windows laptops and particularly for websites and online shops. Outdated software is an easily avoidable risk for you and your customers, since online shops are a favorite target of criminals. As a website operator, it is your job to ensure [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://community.1and1.com/regular-updates-for-security-build-trust/">Regular Updates Establish Security and Build Trust</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://community.1and1.com">1&amp;1 Community</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Philipp Bellmann";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2561:"<p>Only up-to-date software can protect against security holes and attacks. This is true for smartphones, Windows laptops and particularly for websites and online shops.</p>\n<p><strong>Outdated software is an easily avoidable risk</strong> for you and your customers, since online shops are a favorite target of criminals. As a website operator, it is your job to ensure that your installation is always up to date to keep your customers secure.</p>\n<h2>What makes an online shop secure?</h2>\n<p>Secure websites are not a given. To put it simply, the security of your websites and online shops rests on two pillars:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>A secure web hosting platform</strong> with modern security technology, optimized firewalls and server-based protective measures like a security policy to provide a high level of security.</li>\n<li>Modern, reliable <strong>applications (software) with the latest security updates</strong> and appropriate configurations.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>At 1&amp;1, our many teams and security experts work daily to provide you with a secure, reliable and powerful platform for your websites and online shops.</p>\n<p>We rely on your assistance at the application level because the web host usually does not have any control over the software versions you are using. It is up to you to install regular security updates to provide a secure environment for your customers and visitors.</p>\n<p>Large content management systems (CMS) like Magento, WordPress with WooCommerce, PrestaShop and others offer crucial long-term support and <strong>simple update mechanisms. Use these functions regularly and activate automatic security updates</strong> whenever possible.</p>\n<p>This will help lay the foundation for successful and secure online commerce.</p>\n<h2>After a Hack: Getting Assistance</h2>\n<p>The best advice is always to remain calm and implement the correct measures quickly and appropriately. You can find detailed information in the following post: <a href="https://community.1and1.com/how-to-repair-a-hacked-website/">First Steps after a Website Hack</a></p>\n<p><strong>Website security is a complex topic. Do not delay in asking for help</strong>: Our experts at <a href="https://contact.1and1.com">1&amp;1 Web Hosting Customer Service</a> are available around the clock.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://community.1and1.com/regular-updates-for-security-build-trust/">Regular Updates Establish Security and Build Trust</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://community.1and1.com">1&amp;1 Community</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:74:"https://community.1and1.com/regular-updates-for-security-build-trust/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:60:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:76:"Setting Up Two Factor Authentication with WordPress and Google Authenticator";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:94:"https://community.1and1.com/two-factor-authentication-with-wordpress-and-google-authenticator/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:102:"https://community.1and1.com/two-factor-authentication-with-wordpress-and-google-authenticator/#respond";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 09 Jan 2017 07:00:23 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:7:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"How-To";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"WCMS";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"WordPress";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:18:"WordPress Security";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Beginner";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"Getting Started";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:6;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Security";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:36:"https://community.1and1.com/?p=4490/";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:711:"<p>Google Authenticator allows you to combine the classic WordPress login with username and password with an additional security code. This increases the security of your WordPress website. WordPress supports two factor authentication via Google Authenticator with plugins such as Google Authenticator by Hendrik Schack. As a first step, you select the desired authentication method in [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://community.1and1.com/two-factor-authentication-with-wordpress-and-google-authenticator/">Setting Up Two Factor Authentication with WordPress and Google Authenticator</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://community.1and1.com">1&amp;1 Community</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Philipp Bellmann";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5766:"<p><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-4641" src="https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/two-factor-ga-wordpress-vi-300x300.png" alt="two-factor-ga-wordpress-vi" width="300" height="300" srcset="https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/two-factor-ga-wordpress-vi-300x300.png 300w, https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/two-factor-ga-wordpress-vi-150x150.png 150w, https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/two-factor-ga-wordpress-vi.png 500w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" />Google Authenticator allows you to combine the classic WordPress login with username and password with an additional security code. This increases the security of your WordPress website.</p>\n<p>WordPress supports two factor authentication via <em>Google Authenticator</em> with plugins such as <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/google-authenticator/" target="_blank">Google Authenticator by Hendrik Schack</a>.</p>\n<p>As a first step, you select the desired authentication method in the admin area. Afterwards, you can adapt the two-factor authentication for each user individually.</p>\n<p>This means you can explicitly protect admins and exclude authors from the two-factor authentication, for example.</p>\n<h2>Installing Google Authenticator</h2>\n<p>Install the Google Authenticator app on your smartphone: Download: <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/de/app/google-authenticator/id388497605?mt=8" target="_blank">iOS</a> / <a href="https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.google.android.apps.authenticator2" target="_blank">Android</a></p>\n<h2>Installing the Google Authenticator Plugin</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>In the WordPress admin area, select <strong>Plugins</strong>, then <strong>Add New</strong> and search for <em>Google Authenticator</em>.</li>\n<li>Install the <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/google-authenticator/" target="_blank">Google Authenticator</a> plugin by Hendrik Schack.</li>\n</ul>\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-4492" src="https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/wordpress-2fa-install-plugin-en.png" alt="wordpress-2fa-install-plugin-en" width="1247" height="711" srcset="https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/wordpress-2fa-install-plugin-en.png 1247w, https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/wordpress-2fa-install-plugin-en-300x171.png 300w, https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/wordpress-2fa-install-plugin-en-1024x584.png 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1247px) 100vw, 1247px" />\n<ul>\n<li>Activate the <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/google-authenticator/" target="_blank">Google Authenticator</a> plugin by Hendrik Schack.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You can now set up two-factor authentication for your users.</p>\n<h2>Setting Up Two Factor Authentication for Users</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Open the <strong>Users </strong>section.<strong><br />\n</strong></li>\n<li>Select the user for which you would like to enable two-factor authentication.</li>\n<li>Under Google Authenticator Settings, check the option <strong>Active</strong>.</li>\n<li>Click <strong>Show/Hide QR code</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You should now be able to see an automatically generated QR code:</p>\n<a href="https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/wordpess-2fa-settings-en.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-4493" src="https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/wordpess-2fa-settings-en.png" alt="wordpess-2fa-settings-en" width="1247" height="711" srcset="https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/wordpess-2fa-settings-en.png 1247w, https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/wordpess-2fa-settings-en-300x171.png 300w, https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/wordpess-2fa-settings-en-1024x584.png 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1247px) 100vw, 1247px" /></a>\n<ul>\n<li>Open the <em>Google Authenticator</em> app on your smartphone and scan the <strong>QR code</strong>.<br />\nAlternatively, you can also set up your account manually. To do so, use the <strong>description</strong> and <strong>secret</strong> displayed for this user in WordPress.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You can now see a new entry for your website in the <em>Google Authenticator</em> app. The security code is updated every 30 seconds.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Click <strong>Update Profile</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The two-factor authentication is now set up for this user. From now on, use a new security code each time you log in.<a href="https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/wordpress-2fa-login-en.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-4494" src="https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/wordpress-2fa-login-en.png" alt="wordpress-2fa-login-en" width="370" height="497" srcset="https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/wordpress-2fa-login-en.png 370w, https://community.1and1.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/wordpress-2fa-login-en-223x300.png 223w" sizes="(max-width: 370px) 100vw, 370px" /></a></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;">Loggin in with Google Authenticator Code</p>\n<h3>Write Down Secret</h3>\n<p>For situations in which you don&#8217;t have access to the Authenticator, you can fall back on the secret to connect a new Authenticator.</p>\n<p>Store the secret in a secure location. Pretty old-fashioned, but secure: Write it down on a piece of paper.</p>\n<p>That&#8217;s it! Congratulations, your WordPress website has just become a bit more secure!</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://community.1and1.com/two-factor-authentication-with-wordpress-and-google-authenticator/">Setting Up Two Factor Authentication with WordPress and Google Authenticator</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://community.1and1.com">1&amp;1 Community</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:99:"https://c